b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"FPGA-based ternary CPU breaks binary’s 70-year monopoly"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Potential efficiency gains—but no killer app yet"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Industry inertia may smother adoption before it starts"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["For seven decades, binary logic has been computing’s unshakable foundation. Every CPU in your phone, laptop, or car crunches 1s and 0s because, frankly, it’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"easy"}],": cheap to manufacture, simple to design, and backed by trillions in infrastructure. So when a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://hackaday.com/2023/11/ternary-risc-processor-achieves-non-binary-computing-via-fpga/","children":"ternary RISC processor"}],"—using three states (1, 0, and -1) instead of two—emerged from an FPGA prototype, the natural question wasn’t ",["$","em",null,{"children":"how"}],", but ",["$","em",null,{"children":"why now"}],"?\nThe pitch for ternary is seductive on paper. Three states mean more information per clock cycle, which ",["$","em",null,{"children":"could"}]," translate to lower power use or faster parallel math—useful for ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2205.03401","children":"AI acceleration"}]," or signal processing. The FPGA implementation, while not a commercial product, proves the concept works outside labs. Yet here’s the catch: binary’s dominance isn’t technical. It’s economic. Foundries are tooled for 0s and 1s; compilers assume them; even ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06092-1","children":"quantum computing"}]," often defaults to binary qubits for compatibility.\nEarly adopters might include niche embedded systems where power efficiency justifies the overhead. But for 99% of developers, ternary today is like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://riscv.org/about/history/","children":"RISC-V in 2015"}],": theoretically elegant, practically irrelevant until the toolchain catches up. The real test isn’t whether ternary ",["$","em",null,{"children":"can"}]," work—it’s whether anyone will bother rewriting the rulebook for it."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/ternary-cpus-why-binarys-reign-might-finally-be-cr/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A 3-state processor challenges computing’s binary dogma—so why isn’t anyone rushing to use it?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"A 3-state processor challenges computing’s binary dogma—so why isn’t anyone rushing to use it?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The community reaction so far? Polite applause, zero urgency. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://hackaday.com/2023/11/ternary-risc-processor-achieves-non-binary-computing-via-fpga/#comments","children":"Hackaday commenters"}]," praise the hacker spirit but note the lack of a ‘killer app’—no task where ternary is ",["$","em",null,{"children":"obviously"}]," better, not just ",["$","em",null,{"children":"theoretically"}]," cleaner. Even the FPGA route, while flexible, highlights the problem: if ternary were a clear win, why isn’t TSMC or Intel ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://semiwiki.com/semiconductor-manufacturers/tsmc/","children":"betting silicon on it"}],"?\nThen there’s the ecosystem tax. Binary’s inertia is a moat. Every IDE, every OS kernel, every GPU shader assumes two states. Porting that stack to ternary would require a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3579371","children":"decade of coordinated effort"}],"—or a crisis (like the end of Moore’s Law) to force the issue. The closest parallel is ","$L14"," for AI, where efficiency gains justified the pain. Ternary lacks that narrative.\nWhat ","$L15"," work here? The FPGA prototype is a low-risk sandbox for researchers to stress-test ternary’s limits. If a breakthrough emerges—say, a 20% power saving in neural nets—","$L16"," the industry might listen. Until then, this is a footnote in computing’s ‘what if’ file, not a turning point. The signal isn’t the tech; it’s the silence around it."]}]]}]
